    "author_association": "NONE",
    "body": "### Problem\n\nSetting the `'exrc'` option does not source automatically source a `.nvim.lua` file located in the current directory, but does source one located in a parent directory.\n\nPossibly related to #33889.\n\n### Steps to reproduce\n\nMinimal `init.lua` file needed:\n\n```lua\nvim.o.exrc = true\n```\n\nSetting up the directory structure:\n\n```bash\necho \"vim.o.exrc = true\" >init.lua\necho \"print('hello')\" >.nvim.lua\nmkdir -p dir/subdir\nnvim -u init.lua .nvim.lua +trust +q\n```\n\nThe following **does not** show `hello` in the messages when starting neovim:\n\n```bash\nnvim -u init.lua\n```\n\nThe following **does** show `hello` in the messages when starting neovim:\n\n```bash\ncd dir\nnvim -u ../init.lua\n\ncd subdir\nnvim -u ../../init.lua\n```\n\nUsing either `.exrc` or `.nvimrc` with the vimscript `echom \"hello\"` command yields the exact same result\n\n**Sidenote:** either I'm misinterpreting the help string for `:trust`, or passing in a file argument using `:trust .nvim.lua` doesn't work, and throws an `E475: Invalid argument: .nvim.lua` error.\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nI would expect that enabling `'exrc'` also sourced any `.nvim.lua` file in the current directory.\n\n### Nvim version (nvim -v)\n\nv0.12.0-dev-1611+g72110da567\n\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\n\nno, vim v9.1, patches 1-1900\n\n### Operating system/version\n\nmacOS Sequoia 15.7.1\n\n### Terminal name/version\n\nkitty v0.44.0\n\n### $TERM environment variable\n\nxterm-kitty\n\n### Installation\n\nbuild from repo",
